  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and principles\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Facilitate information sharing and evidence exchange\n- Enable cross-border legal proceedings\n\n3. Standardized Regulatory Frameworks\n- Develop consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Establish common reporting requirements\n- Create uniform compliance standards for financial institutions\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Banks required to implement know-your-customer (KYC) procedures\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- International tracking of financial transfers\n\n5. Enforcement Collaboration\n- Interpol and other international law enforcement agencies\n- Coordinated investigations across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering prosecutions\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated financial restrictions\n\n7. Technology and Information Sharing\n- Global financial intelligence networks\n- Digital tracking of suspicious transactions\n- Real-time cross-border monitoring systems\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive approach to combating money laundering internationally.",
